function minSpaceWastedKResizing(nums, k) {
    let n = nums.length;
    let dp = new Array(n + 1).fill(null).map(() => new Array(k + 1).fill(Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER));
    let sum = new Array(n + 1).fill(0);
    dp[0][0] = 0;

    for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        sum[i] = sum[i - 1] + nums[i - 1];
        let max_val = nums[i - 1];
        for (let j = i - 1; j >= 0; j--) {
            max_val = Math.max(max_val, nums[j]);
            let waste = max_val * (i - j) - (sum[i] - sum[j]);
            for (let c = 0; c < k; c++) {
                dp[i][c + 1] = Math.min(dp[i][c + 1], dp[j][c] + waste);
            }
        }
    }
    return dp[n][k];
}
```

    We can use dynamic programming to solve this problem. First, create a DP table with the size (n + 1) x (k + 1), where n is the length of the input nums array.

We initialize the dp table with infinity values (except for dp[0][0] which is 0) to store the minimum waste at each step. Also, create an array called `sum` to store the cumulative sum of `nums`, so we can easily compute the sum of a subarray.

Starting at i = 1, we iterate through each element in nums. At each position i, we go in reverse direction from i-1 to 0. We compute the maximum value and waste value for each subarray nums[j:i]. 

Then, loop from c = 0 to k, and update the DP table as follows: dp[i][c + 1] = min(dp[i][c + 1], dp[j][c] + waste). This represents resizing the array c times by minimizing the total waste.

Finally, return the value dp[n][k].

